{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523162"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.65,0.02,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55857"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"349"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2444"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12900"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55857"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 79-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of redness, itching, and discomfort in her right groin area. She has a medical history of obesity, type 2 diabetes, and hypertension. Her medications include metformin, gliclazide, and amlodipine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is an erythematous, macerated patch with satellite lesions in the right inguinal fold, extending under a fold of abdominal skin (Images 1-2). The area is warm and slightly malodorous.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first-line treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral flucloxacillin","Topical hydrocortisone cream","Topical clotrimazole cream","Oral metronidazole","Topical zinc oxide ointment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with intertrigo, an inflammatory condition occurring in skin folds, often exacerbated by moisture, friction, and secondary infections. The location, appearance, and associated risk factors (obesity, diabetes) strongly suggest this diagnosis. In this case, the presence of satellite lesions indicates likely \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E superinfection, which is common in intertrigo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical clotrimazole cream\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment. Antifungal creams are effective against \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E and can help resolve both the fungal infection and the underlying intertrigo. Clotrimazole also has some antibacterial properties, which can be beneficial if there\u0027s a mixed infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical hydrocortisone cream\u003C/strong\u003E, while potentially helpful for reducing inflammation, is not the best first-line treatment. Steroids can exacerbate fungal infections and potentially thin the skin, which is already compromised in intertrigo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were clear signs of significant bacterial infection, such as cellulitis. However, the description suggests a primarily fungal infection, making topical antifungal treatment more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used for anaerobic bacterial infections and certain protozoal infections. It\u0027s not indicated for intertrigo or \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical zinc oxide ointment\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful as a barrier cream to prevent moisture-associated skin damage, but it\u0027s not an active treatment for the likely fungal infection present in this case. It might be used as an adjunct therapy after the infection is controlled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to antifungal treatment, management should include keeping the area clean and dry, using moisture-wicking fabrics, and considering the use of antiperspirants or absorbent powders. Patient education about weight loss and proper skin fold hygiene is crucial for preventing recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intertrigo is a common inflammatory condition occurring in skin folds, often exacerbated by moisture, friction, and secondary infections.","Topical antifungal agents are first-line treatment for intertrigo, especially when Candida infection is suspected.","Weight loss and proper hygiene are important preventive measures for intertrigo in overweight patients."],"references":["Candidiasis of skin folds. In: DermNet NZ [Online]. dermnetnz.org. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/candidiasis-of-skin-folds","Janniger CK, Schwartz RA, Szepietowski JC, Reich A. Intertrigo and common secondary skin infections. Am Fam Physician. 2005 Sep 1;72(5):833-8. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16156342/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41403"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20816"},{"type":"media","id":"20817"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id"